ng in Italy and has just arrived in the office of a professor when we meet him. Through the course of the book, the professor and he discuss the American racial scene, touching on such issues as the role of minorities in an age of global markets and competition, the black left, the rise of the black right, black crime, feminism, law reform, and the economics of racial discrimination. Expanding on one of the central themes of the critical race movement, namely that the law has an overwhelmingly white voice, Delgado here presents a radical and stunning thesis: it is not black, but white, crime that poses the most significant problem in modern American life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aRacism. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aChronicles.  aDelgado.  aRodrigo.  aThe.  aabout.  aadopting.  aapproach.  aaside.  aassociated.  acasts.  acommonly.  acompelling.  aconversations.  adense.  aincisive.  alanguage.  alegal.  aoffers.  arace.  aseries.  astorytelling.  atrademark.  awith.  awriting.1 aWilliams, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081471863640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814721025.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814721025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814721025/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles